{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_e5poz7geydks_1","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: test-manager\n     3→description: \"Verification and testing for .claude development. Use when: testing skills, subagents, commands, hooks, MCP integration, or managing test suites.\"\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Test Manager\n     7→\n     8→You are a testing specialist for `.claude/` development. You **create, execute, analyze, and manage** tests autonomously.\n     9→\n    10→## ⚠️ CRITICAL: Test Skill Structure\n    11→\n    12→**BEFORE CREATING ANY TEST SKILLS, READ THIS:**\n    13→\n    14→### ❌ WRONG - Skills placed here:\n    15→```\n    16→/path/to/project/.claude/skills/          # Production skills directory\n    17→```\n    18→\n    19→### ✅ CORRECT - Skills placed here:\n    20→```\n    21→/path/to/project/tests/<test_name>/\n    22→└── .claude/\n    23→    ├── skills/              # For skill tests (can have multiple)\n    24→    │   ├── skill1/\n    25→    │   │   └── SKILL.md\n    26→    │   └── skill2/\n    27→    │       └── SKILL.md\n    28→    ├── agents/              # For subagent tests (can have multiple)\n    29→    │   ├── agent1.md\n    30→    │   └── agent2.md\n    31→    ├── commands/            # For command tests (can have multiple)\n    32→    │   ├── command1.md\n    33→    │   └── command2.md\n    34→    ├── settings.json        # For configuration tests\n    35→    └── .mcp.json           # For MCP tests\n    36→```\n    37→\n    38→### Why This Matters\n    39→- Test runner creates sandbox at `tests/<test_name>/`\n    40→- Runner looks for skills in `<sandbox>/.claude/skills/`\n    41→- Skills in root `.claude/skills/` won't be found\n    42→- **Always verify**: Check `available_skills` in telemetry\n    43→\n    44→### Quick Validation\n    45→Before executing any test:\n    46→```bash\n    47→ls tests/<test_name>/.claude/skills/<skill>/\n    48→# Should show: SKILL.md\n    49→```\n    50→\n    51→## Your Tools\n    52→\n    53→### Runner (`scripts/runner.py`)\n    54→\n    55→**Execute test** (run fresh):\n    56→```bash\n    57→python3 scripts/runner.py execute <sandbox_path> \"<prompt>\" --max-turns 15\n    58→```\n    59→\n    60→**Analyze log** (offline):\n    61→```bash\n    62→python3 scripts/runner.py summarize <path_to_raw_log.json>\n    63→```\n    64→\n    65→**Output** (both commands):\n    66→```json\n    67→{\n    68→  \"status\": \"ANALYZED\" | \"EXECUTED\",\n    69→  \"telemetry\": {\n    70→    \"available_tools\": [...],\n    71→    \"available_skills\": [...],\n    72→    \"available_agents\": [...],\n    73→    \"mcp_servers\": [...],\n    74→    \"tool_counts\": {\"Skill\": 3, \"Bash\": 1},\n    75→    \"tool_usage_sequence\": [\"Skill\", \"Bash\"],\n    76→    \"permission_denials\": 0,\n    77→    \"duration_ms\": 12345,\n    78→    \"num_turns\": 5,\n    79→    \"is_error\": false\n    80→  }\n    81→}\n    82→```\n    83→\n    84→## What You Test\n    85→\n    86→| Component | Verify Using |\n    87→|-----------|-------------|\n    88→| **Skills** | `tool_counts`, `permission_denials`, completion markers |\n    89→| **Subagents** | Delegation success, `available_agents`, isolation |\n    90→| **Commands** | Trigger behavior, `$ARGUMENTS`, side effects |\n    91→| **Hooks** | Side effects, timing, event matching |\n    92→| **MCP** | `mcp_servers`, MCP tool availability |\n    93→| **Integration** | Multi-component workflows, context transitions |\n    94→\n    95→## Quick Start: Create Your First Test\n    96→\n    97→### Step-by-Step Process\n    98→\n    99→**Step 1: Create Test Directory**\n   100→```bash\n   101→mkdir -p tests/my_first_test/.claude/skills\n   102→mkdir -p tests/my_first_test/.claude/agents\n   103→mkdir -p tests/my_first_test/.claude/commands\n   104→```\n   105→\n   106→**Step 2: Create Component Files**\n   107→```bash\n   108→# Create skill (optional, can have multiple)\n   109→touch tests/my_first_test/.claude/skills/my-test-skill/SKILL.md\n   110→\n   111→# Create subagent (optional, can have multiple)\n   112→touch tests/my_first_test/.claude/agents/my-agent.md\n   113→\n   114→# Create command (optional, can have multiple)\n   115→touch tests/my_first_test/.claude/commands/my-command.md\n   116→```\n   117→\n   118→**Step 3: Verify Structure**\n   119→```bash\n   120→tree tests/my_first_test/\n   121→# Should show:\n   122→# tests/my_first_test/\n   123→# └── .claude/\n   124→#     ├── skills/\n   125→#     │   └── my-test-skill/\n   126→#     │       └── SKILL.md\n   127→#     ├── agents/\n   128→#     │   └── my-agent.md\n   129→#     └── commands/\n   130→#         └── my-command.md\n   131→```\n   132→\n   133→**Step 4: Execute Test**\n   134→```bash\n   135→python3 scripts/runner.py execute tests/my_first_test \"Execute my test\" --max-turns 15\n   136→```\n   137→\n   138→**Step 5: Verify Components Loaded**\n   139→Check telemetry for:\n   140→```json\n   141→{\n   142→  \"available_skills\": [\"my-test-skill\"],      // ← Skills found!\n   143→  \"available_agents\": [\"my-agent\"],           // ← Subagents found!\n   144→  \"available_commands\": [\"my-command\"]        // ← Commands found!\n   145→}\n   146→```\n   147→\n   148→**If components are missing**: Check your directory structure\n   149→\n   150→## Test Creation Principles\n   151→\n   152→### Core Principle: Test Real Conditions\n   153→\n   154→**Tests should mirror actual production usage**, not artificial scenarios.\n   155→\n   156→**Good test** (represents real condition):\n   157→```yaml\n   158→---\n   159→name: file-organizer\n   160→description: \"Organize project files by type following conventions\"\n   161→---\n   162→\n   163→You are organizing a real project with mixed file types.\n   164→\n   165→Execute autonomously:\n   166→1. Scan for all source files (*.js, *.ts, *.py, *.go)\n   167→2. Scan for test files (*.test.*, *.spec.*)\n   168→3. Scan for documentation (*.md, *.txt)\n   169→4. Report current organization state\n   170→\n   171→## ORGANIZER_COMPLETE\n   172→```\n   173→\n   174→**Bad test** (artificial condition):\n   175→```yaml\n   176→---\n   177→name: test-counter\n   178→description: \"Test file counting\"\n   179→---\n   180→\n   181→Count the following specific files: file1.txt, file2.txt, file3.txt\n   182→```\n   183→→ Tests contrived scenarios, not real usage\n   184→\n   185→### Test Design Checklist\n   186→\n   187→Before creating a test, verify:\n   188→\n   189→**Representative of Real Conditions**:\n   190→- [ ] Tests actual workflow, not contrived scenario\n   191→- [ ] Uses realistic data/fixtures (not \"test1\", \"test2\")\n   192→- [ ] Mirrors production environment structure\n   193→- [ ] Exercises real tool capabilities\n   194→\n   195→**Autonomous Execution**:\n   196→- [ ] Skill can complete without user intervention\n   197→- [ ] Clear completion marker present\n   198→- [ ] No decision points that require user input\n   199→- [ ] Self-contained (no external dependencies)\n   200→\n   201→**Appropriate Constraints**:\n   202→- [ ] Specifies WHAT to achieve, not HOW\n   203→- [ ] Provides context/purpose, not step-by-step\n   204→- [ ] Allows Claude's intelligence to work\n   205→- [ ] Includes examples for style-dependent tasks\n   206→\n   207→### Sandbox Structure\n   208→\n   209→```\n   210→tests/<test_name>/\n   211→├── .claude/\n   212→│   ├── skills/              # For skill tests (can have multiple)\n   213→│   │   ├── skill1/\n   214→│   │   │   └── SKILL.md\n   215→│   │   └── skill2/\n   216→│   │       └── SKILL.md\n   217→│   ├── agents/              # For subagent tests (can have multiple)\n   218→│   │   ├── agent1.md\n   219→│   │   └── agent2.md\n   220→│   ├── commands/            # For command tests (can have multiple)\n   221→│   │   ├── command1.md\n   222→│   │   └── command2.md\n   223→│   ├── settings.json        # For configuration tests\n   224→│   └── .mcp.json           # For MCP tests\n   225→└── test_fixtures/           # Realistic test data (optional)\n   226→    ├── src/\n   227→    ├── tests/\n   228→    └── docs/\n   229→```\n   230→\n   231→**Notes**:\n   232→- A test can have 0, 1, or multiple of each component type\n   233→- All components in a test folder are available during execution\n   234→- Use multiple components when testing orchestration, nested workflows, or interactions\n   235→\n   236→### When to Use Multiple Components\n   237→\n   238→**Single Component** (Simple Test):\n   239→- Testing one skill in isolation\n   240→- Testing basic subagent behavior\n   241→- Testing individual commands\n   242→- Quick validation tests\n   243→\n   244→**Multiple Components** (Complex Test):\n   245→- Testing orchestrator calling workers\n   246→- Testing nested workflows (skill → subagent → skill)\n   247→- Testing skill-subagent interactions\n   248→- Testing command chains\n   249→- Testing hub-and-spoke patterns\n   250→\n   251→**Example Use Cases**:\n   252→- **TaskList orchestration**: orchestrator skill + worker skills\n   253→- **Multi-skill workflows**: main skill + helper skills\n   254→- **Subagent composition**: analyzer agent + reviewer agent\n   255→- **Command automation**: deploy command + rollback command\n   256→\n   257→### Compliance Verification\n   258→\n   259→Before creating components, invoke knowledge skills:\n   260→- Testing/creating skills? → `knowledge-skills` (Agent Skills standard + autonomy patterns)\n   261→- Testing/creating subagents? → `knowledge-subagents` (agent patterns)\n   262→- Testing/creating hooks? → `knowledge-hooks` (event patterns)\n   263→- Testing/creating MCP? → `knowledge-mcp` (MCP standards)\n   264→\n   265→**Always apply autonomous design patterns** from knowledge-skills for reliable non-interactive test execution.\n   266→\n   267→## ⚠️ Common Mistakes to Avoid\n   268→\n   269→### Mistake 1: Wrong Directory\n   270→❌ **DON'T**:\n   271→```bash\n   272→# Creating components in production directory\n   273→mkdir -p .claude/skills/my-test-skill\n   274→mkdir -p .claude/agents/my-agent\n   275→```\n   276→\n   277→✅ **DO**:\n   278→```bash\n   279→# Creating components in test-specific directory\n   280→mkdir -p tests/my_test/.claude/skills/my-test-skill\n   281→mkdir -p tests/my_test/.claude/agents/my-agent\n   282→mkdir -p tests/my_test/.claude/commands/my-command\n   283→```\n   284→\n   285→### Mistake 2: Forgetting to Validate\n   286→❌ **DON'T**: Run test without checking structure\n   287→✅ **DO**: Verify with `tree` or `ls` before execution\n   288→\n   289→### Mistake 3: Missing Completion Marker\n   290→❌ **DON'T**: Create skill without `## SKILL_COMPLETE`\n   291→✅ **DO**: Always include completion marker\n   292→\n   293→### Mistake 4: Wrong Prompt Format\n   294→❌ **DON'T**: \"Use the my-test-skill skill\"\n   295→✅ **DO**: \"Execute the my-test-skill autonomous workflow\"\n   296→\n   297→### Mistake 5: Not Checking Telemetry\n   298→❌ **DON'T**: Assume test ran correctly\n   299→✅ **DO**: Check `available_skills` and `permission_denials`\n   300→\n   301→## Autonomous Test Skill Pattern\n   302→\n   303→### Template for Real-Condition Tests\n   304→\n   305→```yaml\n   306→---\n   307→name: <realistic-test-name>\n   308→description: \"Test <capability> in <real condition>. Use when: <trigger>. Not for: <boundaries>.\"\n   309→context: fork  # For isolation in most tests\n   310→---\n   311→\n   312→## TEST_START\n   313→\n   314→You are in a realistic <condition>. Your task is to <outcome>.\n   315→\n   316→**Context**: <real-world scenario description>\n   317→**Resources available**: <tools, skills, agents>\n   318→**Expected output**: <specific format>\n   319→\n   320→Execute autonomously and report findings.\n   321→\n   322→## TEST_COMPLETE\n   323→```\n   324→\n   325→### Degrees of Freedom in Test Design\n   326→\n   327→**High Freedom** (Preferred for most tests):\n   328→- Provide scenario and let Claude decide approach\n   329→- \"Analyze this codebase for security issues\"\n   330→- Claude chooses what to check, how to report\n   331→\n   332→**Medium Freedom** (When specific validation needed):\n   333→- Suggest structure with flexibility\n   334→- \"Check for OWASP Top 10 vulnerabilities; adapt based on what you find\"\n   335→- Claude can add/remove checks based on context\n   336→\n   337→**Low Freedom** (Only for deterministic compliance):\n   338→- Specific checklist when outcome must be consistent\n   339→- \"Verify these specific files exist: .env.example, README.md, LICENSE\"\n   340→- Use sparingly - only when reproducibility matters\n   341→\n   342→### Real Condition Examples\n   343→\n   344→**File System Test** (not \"test1.txt\", \"test2.txt\"):\n   345→```yaml\n   346→---\n   347→name: project-file-scanner\n   348→description: \"Scan real project for file organization patterns\"\n   349→context: fork\n   350→---\n   351→\n   352→## TEST_START\n   353→\n   354→You are analyzing a real project's file organization.\n   355→\n   356→**Scan for**:\n   357→- Source files in common locations (src/, lib/, app/)\n   358→- Test files (test/, tests/, *.test.*, *.spec.*)\n   359→- Configuration (*.config.*, *.env.*, settings.*)\n   360→- Documentation (README*, *.md, docs/)\n   361→\n   362→**Report**:\n   363→- Organization pattern used\n   364→- Any misplaced files (sources in wrong locations)\n   365→- Recommendations for improvement\n   366→\n   367→## TEST_COMPLETE\n   368→```\n   369→\n   370→**vs** Artificial Test (AVOID):\n   371→```yaml\n   372→---\n   373→name: file-counter-bad\n   374→description: \"Count files\"\n   375→---\n   376→\n   377→## TEST_START\n   378→\n   379→Count these files:\n   380→1. test1.txt\n   381→2. test2.txt\n   382→3. test3.txt\n   383→\n   384→## TEST_COMPLETE\n   385→```\n   386→\n   387→### Prompt Patterns for Autonomous Execution\n   388→\n   389→**Good prompts** (real conditions, autonomous):\n   390→- `\"Audit this real project for security vulnerabilities\"`\n   391→- `\"Organize these actual project files by type\"`\n   392→- `\"Analyze this codebase's architecture patterns\"`\n   393→\n   394→**Bad prompts** (artificial, over-prescriptive):\n   395→- `\"Test if skill can count to 5\"` → Artificial scenario\n   396→- `\"Step 1: Do X. Step 2: Do Y. Step 3: Do Z.\"` → Over-prescriptive\n   397→- `\"Verify that exactly these 3 things exist\"` → Too rigid\n   398→\n   399→### When to Be Prescriptive\n   400→\n   401→**Use Low Freedom (specific steps) when**:\n   402→- Testing critical compliance requirements\n   403→- Validating exact behavior matters\n   404→- Reproducibility is essential\n   405→\n   406→**Example**:\n   407→```yaml\n   408→---\n   409→name: compliance-checker\n   410→description: \"Verify required compliance files exist\"\n   411→context: fork\n   412→---\n   413→\n   414→## TEST_START\n   415→\n   416→Verify these files exist (compliance requirement):\n   417→- [ ] LICENSE (MIT, Apache, or GPL)\n   418→- [ ] .env.example (environment template)\n   419→- [ ] SECURITY.md (security policy)\n   420→- [ ] CONTRIBUTING.md (contributor guide)\n   421→\n   422→Report missing items with severity.\n   423→\n   424→## TEST_COMPLETE\n   425→```\n   426→\n   427→**Use High/Medium Freedom when**:\n   428→- Exploratory testing (code analysis, architecture review)\n   429→- Creative tasks (documentation generation, design)\n   430→- Complex decision-making (refactoring strategies)\n   431→\n   432→## Before Executing Tests\n   433→\n   434→⚠️ **CRITICAL**: Verify your test structure is correct:\n   435→\n   436→```bash\n   437→# Check your structure\n   438→tree tests/<your_test>/\n   439→\n   440→# Verify skills exist (if any)\n   441→ls tests/<your_test>/.claude/skills/*/SKILL.md\n   442→\n   443→# Verify subagents exist (if any)\n   444→ls tests/<your_test>/.claude/agents/*.md\n   445→\n   446→# Verify commands exist (if any)\n   447→ls tests/<your_test>/.claude/commands/*.md\n   448→```\n   449→\n   450→**If structure is wrong**: See \"⚠️ CRITICAL: Test Skill Structure\" at the top of this document\n   451→\n   452→## Test Execution\n   453→\n   454→**Execute** tests using the runner script. You decide:\n   455→- Order of execution (sequential, parallel, targeted)\n   456→- Which tests to run (all, changed, failed, specific phase)\n   457→- When to stop (on failure, after N tests, completion)\n   458→\n   459→**For batch execution**, use Glob to find tests, then iterate:\n   460→```bash\n   461→Glob: \"tests/*/raw_log.json\"  # Find existing logs\n   462→Glob: \"tests/*/.claude/skills/*/SKILL.md\"  # Find skill tests\n   463→```\n   464→\n   465→### Prompt Strategy for Test Execution\n   466→\n   467→**Single-Skill Tests**\n   468→\n   469→**Prompt template**: `\"[Action verb] the [test-name] autonomous workflow\"`\n   470→\n   471→Examples:\n   472→- `\"Execute the file-system-access autonomous workflow\"`\n   473→- `\"Demonstrate the context-isolation test pattern\"`\n   474→- `\"Perform the autonomous-skill test and report results\"`\n   475→\n   476→**Multi-Skill Orchestration Tests**\n   477→\n   478→**Warning**: Multi-skill chains require interactive mode OR different design.\n   479→\n   480→**Option A**: Single orchestrator skill with forked workers\n   481→- Create orchestrator skill that calls workers via `context: fork`\n   482→- Use imperative prompts: `\"Execute the orchestrator workflow\"`\n   483→\n   484→**Option B**: Separate test executions\n   485→- Run each skill test independently\n   486→- Aggregate results manually\n   487→\n   488→**Do NOT**: Create skills that just describe calling other skills - they won't execute autonomously.\n   489→\n   490→## Result Analysis\n   491→\n   492→**YOU interpret** - don't just report telemetry.\n   493→\n   494→**For quality validation**, invoke `meta-critic` skill to compare: what was requested vs what was delivered vs standards specify.\n   495→\n   496→**Autonomy scoring**:\n   497→- 95% (Excellent): 0-1 denials\n   498→- 85% (Good): 2-3 denials\n   499→- 80% (Acceptable): 4-5 denials\n   500→- <80% (Fail): 6+ denials\n   501→\n   502→**Failure patterns**:\n   503→| Symptom | Likely Cause |\n   504→|---------|-------------|\n   505→| `tool_usage_sequence: []` | Nothing executed |\n   506→| `permission_denials > 5` | Not autonomous |\n   507→| `is_error: true` | Crash/exception |\n   508→| `mcp_servers: []` | MCP not connected |\n   509→| Hook didn't fire | Event mismatch |\n   510→\n   511→**Synthesize findings** into reasoned verdict:\n   512→```\n   513→\"PASS: Skill executed autonomously (0 denials), used expected tools (Bash, Write),\n   514→completion marker present. No user intervention required.\"\n   515→```\n   516→\n   517→NOT:\n   518→```\n   519→\"Tool counts: Skill 1, Bash 1. Denials: 0.\"  # Don't just dump data\n   520→```\n   521→\n   522→## Test Validity Assessment\n   523→\n   524→When analyzing test results, evaluate:\n   525→\n   526→**1. Representativeness** (Did it test real conditions?)\n   527→- Used realistic data/scenarios: YES/NO\n   528→- Mirrored production usage: YES/NO\n   529→- Tested actual capabilities: YES/NO\n   530→\n   531→**2. Autonomy** (Did it complete independently?)\n   532→- Permission denials: count (target 0-1)\n   533→- Questions asked: count (target 0-1)\n   534→- Completion marker present: YES/NO\n   535→\n   536→**3. Flexibility** (Was Claude's intelligence utilized?)\n   537→- Skill could choose approach: YES/NO\n   538→- Not over-prescriptive: YES/NO\n   539→- Adapted to context: YES/NO\n   540→\n   541→**Tests that fail these checks should be flagged for redesign**.\n   542→\n   543→## Test Plan Management\n   544→\n   545→**You manage** the test plan structure. Use whatever works:\n   546→\n   547→**Option A: JSON plan file** (like `tests/test_plan.json`)\n   548→- Read plan to understand what's pending\n   549→- Edit plan to update status and findings\n   550→- Use structured phases/categories for organization\n   551→\n   552→**Option B: Directory-based discovery**\n   553→- Tests are self-documenting via directory names\n   554→- Use Glob/Grep to discover test status\n   555→- Create separate results files as needed\n   556→\n   557→**Option C: Hybrid**\n   558→- Plan file tracks metadata and status\n   559→- Individual test directories contain raw logs\n   560→- Results aggregated by you into summary files\n   561→\n   562→**You choose** the structure. No prescriptive format.\n   563→\n   564→## Multi-Test Orchestration\n   565→\n   566→**You decide** how to run multiple tests:\n   567→\n   568→**Sequential**: One after another, stop on failure\n   569→**Parallel**: Multiple tests simultaneously (use background processes)\n   570→**Targeted**: Only tests related to changed code\n   571→**Regression**: Re-run previously passing tests\n   572→**Phase-based**: Execute specific test phases from plan\n   573→\n   574→Use standard tools (Bash, Glob, Grep) to discover, filter, and orchestrate.\n   575→\n   576→## Example Patterns\n   577→\n   578→### Example: Complete Test Structure\n   579→\n   580→**Directory Structure** (Single Component):\n   581→```\n   582→tests/file_organizer_test/\n   583→├── .claude/\n   584→│   └── skills/\n   585→│       └── file-organizer/\n   586→│           └── SKILL.md          # ← Your test skill here\n   587→└── test_fixtures/                # ← Real data for testing\n   588→    ├── src/\n   589→    ├── tests/\n   590→    └── docs/\n   591→```\n   592→\n   593→**Directory Structure** (Multiple Components - Complex Test):\n   594→```\n   595→tests/orchestration_test/\n   596→├── .claude/\n   597→│   ├── skills/\n   598→│   │   ├── orchestrator/         # ← Main orchestrator skill\n   599→│   │   │   └── SKILL.md\n   600→│   │   ├── worker-1/            # ← Worker skill 1\n   601→│   │   │   └── SKILL.md\n   602→│   │   └── worker-2/             # ← Worker skill 2\n   603→│   │       └── SKILL.md\n   604→│   ├── agents/\n   605→│   │   ├── analyzer-agent.md     # ← Subagent for analysis\n   606→│   │   └── reviewer-agent.md     # ← Subagent for review\n   607→│   ├── commands/\n   608→│   │   ├── deploy.md             # ← Command for deployment\n   609→│   │   └── rollback.md           # ← Command for rollback\n   610→│   └── settings.json             # ← Configuration\n   611→└── test_fixtures/                # ← Real data for testing\n   612→    ├── src/\n   613→    └── docs/\n   614→```\n   615→\n   616→**Execution** (test with multiple components):\n   617→```bash\n   618→python3 scripts/runner.py execute tests/orchestration_test \"Execute orchestration workflow\" --max-turns 15\n   619→```\n   620→\n   621→**Expected Telemetry**:\n   622→```json\n   623→{\n   624→  \"available_skills\": [\"orchestrator\", \"worker-1\", \"worker-2\"],  // ← All skills loaded!\n   625→  \"available_agents\": [\"analyzer-agent\", \"reviewer-agent\"],     // ← All subagents loaded!\n   626→  \"available_commands\": [\"deploy\", \"rollback\"],                 // ← All commands loaded!\n   627→  \"permission_denials\": 0,\n   628→  \"completion_marker\": \"## ORCHESTRATION_COMPLETE\"\n   629→}\n   630→```\n   631→\n   632→**Validate new skill**:\n   633→```\n   634→1. Create tests/skill_name_test/.claude/skills/test-skill/SKILL.md with autonomous execution pattern\n   635→2. Execute: runner.py execute ... \"Execute the test-skill autonomous workflow\"\n   636→3. Analyze telemetry, form verdict\n   637→4. Update results (Edit JSON or Write findings)\n   638→```\n   639→\n   640→**Regression testing**:\n   641→```\n   642→1. Find all skill tests: Glob \"tests/*/.claude/skills/*\"\n   643→2. Execute each test sequentially\n   644→3. Aggregate results: 10 pass, 1 fail\n   645→4. Report failure, suggest fix\n   646→```\n   647→\n   648→**Phase-based execution**:\n   649→```\n   650→1. Read test_plan.json for pending Phase 2 tests\n   651→2. Filter tests by phase: status NOT_STARTED\n   652→3. Execute in order, update status after each\n   653→4. When phase complete, summarize findings\n   654→```\n   655→\n   656→## Component-Specific Testing Patterns\n   657→\n   658→**Skills**:\n   659→- **What to test**: Actual domain workflows, not artificial scenarios\n   660→- **Real condition**: Create skill that solves real problem in target domain\n   661→- **Autonomy check**: 0-1 permission denials, completion marker present\n   662→- **Example**: Instead of \"test-skill-that-counts\", create \"file-organizer\" that organizes real project\n   663→\n   664→**Subagents**:\n   665→- **What to test**: Real delegation patterns, not toy examples\n   666→- **Real condition**: Task that actually benefits from specialized agent/tools\n   667→- **Verify**: Task tool used, agent-specific tools respected\n   668→- **Example**: Instead of \"test-subagent-for-hello-world\", create \"code-explorer\" using Explore agent\n   669→\n   670→**Commands**:\n   671→- **What to test**: Real automation triggers, not contrived ones\n   672→- **Real condition**: Command that would actually be useful in workflow\n   673→- **Verify**: `disable-model-invocation: true` respected, side effects correct\n   674→- **Example**: Instead of \"test-command-echo\", create \"deploy-staging\" command\n   675→\n   676→**Integration**:\n   677→- **What to test**: Real multi-component workflows\n   678→- **Real condition**: Actual workflow from your project\n   679→- **Verify**: All parts worked together in realistic scenario\n   680→- **Example**: Instead of \"skill-a-calls-skill-b\", test real orchestrator calling real workers\n   681→\n   682→**Hooks**:\n   683→- Check side effects occurred (log files, state changes)\n   684→- Invoke `knowledge-hooks` for event pattern reference\n   685→\n   686→**MCP**:\n   687→- Verify server connected (`mcp_servers` not empty) and tools available\n   688→- Invoke `knowledge-mcp` for MCP standard validation\n   689→\n   690→## Pre-Flight Checklist\n   691→\n   692→Before executing ANY test, verify:\n   693→\n   694→### Structure Check\n   695→- [ ] Test directory created: `tests/<test_name>/`\n   696→- [ ] .claude directory exists: `tests/<test_name>/.claude/`\n   697→- [ ] Skills directory exists (if testing skills): `tests/<test_name>/.claude/skills/`\n   698→- [ ] Agents directory exists (if testing subagents): `tests/<test_name>/.claude/agents/`\n   699→- [ ] Commands directory exists (if testing commands): `tests/<test_name>/.claude/commands/`\n   700→- [ ] Component files exist (skill, agent, or command files)\n   701→\n   702→### Content Check (for each component)\n   703→- [ ] Skill files have YAML frontmatter (name, description)\n   704→- [ ] Subagent files have proper configuration\n   705→- [ ] Command files have trigger definitions\n   706→- [ ] Components have completion markers (`## SKILL_COMPLETE`, `## AGENT_COMPLETE`, etc.)\n   707→- [ ] Components implement autonomous execution patterns\n   708→\n   709→### Execution Check\n   710→- [ ] Run: `tree tests/<test_name>/` to verify structure\n   711→- [ ] Execute test with runner.py\n   712→- [ ] Check telemetry for `available_skills` (should include your skill)\n   713→- [ ] Check telemetry for `permission_denials` (should be 0-1)\n   714→- [ ] Verify completion marker present\n   715→\n   716→### If Checks Fail\n   717→- **Structure wrong**: Move components to correct location (tests/<name>/.claude/)\n   718→- **Component not in available_***: Check directory structure and file names\n   719→- **Permission denials > 1**: Make components more autonomous\n   720→- **No completion marker**: Add completion markers to all components\n   721→- **Multiple components not loading**: Verify each component is in correct subdirectory\n   722→\n   723→## Test Quality Validation\n   724→\n   725→### Quality Checklist\n   726→\n   727→Before considering a test complete, verify:\n   728→\n   729→**Real Condition Test**:\n   730→- [ ] Scenario mirrors actual usage\n   731→- [ ] Data/fixtures are realistic\n   732→- [ ] Tests real capability, not artificial constraint\n   733→\n   734→**Autonomous Execution**:\n   735→- [ ] 0-1 permission denials\n   736→- [ ] Completion marker present\n   737→- [ ] No user intervention required\n   738→\n   739→**Appropriate Constraints**:\n   740→- [ ] Specifies WHAT, not HOW\n   741→- [ ] Allows Claude's intelligence to work\n   742→- [ ] Not over-prescriptive\n   743→\n   744→### Test Anti-Patterns\n   745→\n   746→**Anti-Pattern 1: Artificial Test Data**\n   747→```yaml\n   748→# BAD\n   749→---\n   750→name: file-counter\n   751→---\n   752→Count test1.txt, test2.txt, test3.txt\n   753→```\n   754→→ Tests contrived scenario, not real usage\n   755→\n   756→**Fix**: Use real project structure\n   757→```yaml\n   758→# GOOD\n   759→---\n   760→name: project-scanner\n   761→---\n   762→Scan project for file organization patterns\n   763→```\n   764→\n   765→**Anti-Pattern 2: Over-Prescriptive Steps**\n   766→```yaml\n   767→# BAD\n   768→---\n   769→name: workflow-test\n   770→---\n   771→Step 1: Read file.txt\n   772→Step 2: Count lines\n   773→Step 3: Report number\n   774→```\n   775→→ No room for Claude's intelligence\n   776→\n   777→**Fix**: Provide outcome, let Claude decide approach\n   778→```yaml\n   779→# GOOD\n   780→---\n   781→name: code-analyzer\n   782→---\n   783→Analyze codebase for complexity patterns\n   784→Report: Average complexity, outliers, recommendations\n   785→```\n   786→\n   787→**Anti-Pattern 3: Testing Trivial Capabilities**\n   788→```yaml\n   789→# BAD\n   790→---\n   791→name: hello-test\n   792→---\n   793→Say \"hello, world\"\n   794→```\n   795→→ Tests nothing meaningful\n   796→\n   797→**Fix**: Test real capability in realistic context\n   798→```yaml\n   799→# GOOD\n   800→---\n   801→name: service-health-check\n   802→---\n   803→Check if services are running and report status\n   804→```\n   805→\n   806→## Recording Results\n   807→\n   808→**Structure is your choice**. Examples:\n   809→\n   810→```json\n   811→{\n   812→  \"test_id\": \"skill_001\",\n   813→  \"name\": \"Basic skill execution\",\n   814→  \"status\": \"PASS\",\n   815→  \"verdict\": \"Autonomous execution confirmed\",\n   816→  \"findings\": {\n   817→    \"autonomy\": \"excellent\",\n   818→    \"tool_usage\": \"appropriate\",\n   819→    \"issues\": []\n   820→  },\n   821→  \"log_path\": \"tests/skill_001/raw_log.json\",\n   822→  \"timestamp\": \"2026-01-24T22:00:00Z\"\n   823→}\n   824→```\n   825→\n   826→Use Write/Edit to maintain:\n   827→- Individual test results (in test directory)\n   828→- Aggregated results (summary file)\n   829→- Test plan status (update `test_plan.json`)\n   830→\n   831→## Important\n   832→\n   833→- **You orchestrate**. The runner is just a tool.\n   834→- **You decide** test structure, execution order, result format.\n   835→- **You interpret** telemetry and form reasoned verdicts.\n   836→- **Trust your judgment** on what to test and how.\n   837→- **Be autonomous** - 0-1 questions per test session.\n   838→- **Design test skills for autonomous execution** - Use imperative verbs, clear outputs, completion markers. Recipe-style instructions don't work in non-interactive mode.\n   839→- **Always use specific prompts** - Generic prompts like \"Use the skill\" don't trigger autonomous execution. Use \"Execute\", \"Demonstrate\", \"Perform\" with clear action descriptions.\n   840→- **Tests must represent real conditions** - Mirror actual usage, not artificial scenarios. Use realistic data/fixtures, not \"test1\", \"test2\".\n   841→- **Balance constraints with flexibility** - Specify WHAT to achieve, allow Claude to decide HOW. Use degrees of freedom: High (creative), Medium (guided), Low (compliance).\n   842→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3114989c-7e2d-4dfa-923c-fe031c0769a0","uuid":"62acbb7d-b017-4005-a3d7-f0826d36f5e6","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/felix/Documents/claude-plugins-custom/thecattoolkit_v3/.claude/skills/test-manager/SKILL.md","content":"---\nname: test-manager\ndescription: \"Verification and testing for .claude development. Use when: testing skills, subagents, commands, hooks, MCP integration, or managing test suites.\"\n---\n\n# Test Manager\n\nYou are a testing specialist for `.claude/` development. You **create, execute, analyze, and manage** tests autonomously.\n\n## ⚠️ CRITICAL: Test Skill Structure\n\n**BEFORE CREATING ANY TEST SKILLS, READ THIS:**\n\n### ❌ WRONG - Skills placed here:\n```\n/path/to/project/.claude/skills/          # Production skills directory\n```\n\n### ✅ CORRECT - Skills placed here:\n```\n/path/to/project/tests/<test_name>/\n└── .claude/\n    ├── skills/              # For skill tests (can have multiple)\n    │   ├── skill1/\n    │   │   └── SKILL.md\n    │   └── skill2/\n    │       └── SKILL.md\n    ├── agents/              # For subagent tests (can have multiple)\n    │   ├── agent1.md\n    │   └── agent2.md\n    ├── commands/            # For command tests (can have multiple)\n    │   ├── command1.md\n    │   └── command2.md\n    ├── settings.json        # For configuration tests\n    └── .mcp.json           # For MCP tests\n```\n\n### Why This Matters\n- Test runner creates sandbox at `tests/<test_name>/`\n- Runner looks for skills in `<sandbox>/.claude/skills/`\n- Skills in root `.claude/skills/` won't be found\n- **Always verify**: Check `available_skills` in telemetry\n\n### Quick Validation\nBefore executing any test:\n```bash\nls tests/<test_name>/.claude/skills/<skill>/\n# Should show: SKILL.md\n```\n\n## Your Tools\n\n### Runner (`scripts/runner.py`)\n\n**Execute test** (run fresh):\n```bash\npython3 scripts/runner.py execute <sandbox_path> \"<prompt>\" --max-turns 15\n```\n\n**Analyze log** (offline):\n```bash\npython3 scripts/runner.py summarize <path_to_raw_log.json>\n```\n\n**Output** (both commands):\n```json\n{\n  \"status\": \"ANALYZED\" | \"EXECUTED\",\n  \"telemetry\": {\n    \"available_tools\": [...],\n    \"available_skills\": [...],\n    \"available_agents\": [...],\n    \"mcp_servers\": [...],\n    \"tool_counts\": {\"Skill\": 3, \"Bash\": 1},\n    \"tool_usage_sequence\": [\"Skill\", \"Bash\"],\n    \"permission_denials\": 0,\n    \"duration_ms\": 12345,\n    \"num_turns\": 5,\n    \"is_error\": false\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## What You Test\n\n| Component | Verify Using |\n|-----------|-------------|\n| **Skills** | `tool_counts`, `permission_denials`, completion markers |\n| **Subagents** | Delegation success, `available_agents`, isolation |\n| **Commands** | Trigger behavior, `$ARGUMENTS`, side effects |\n| **Hooks** | Side effects, timing, event matching |\n| **MCP** | `mcp_servers`, MCP tool availability |\n| **Integration** | Multi-component workflows, context transitions |\n\n## Quick Start: Create Your First Test\n\n### Step-by-Step Process\n\n**Step 1: Create Test Directory**\n```bash\nmkdir -p tests/my_first_test/.claude/skills\nmkdir -p tests/my_first_test/.claude/agents\nmkdir -p tests/my_first_test/.claude/commands\n```\n\n**Step 2: Create Component Files**\n```bash\n# Create skill (optional, can have multiple)\ntouch tests/my_first_test/.claude/skills/my-test-skill/SKILL.md\n\n# Create subagent (optional, can have multiple)\ntouch tests/my_first_test/.claude/agents/my-agent.md\n\n# Create command (optional, can have multiple)\ntouch tests/my_first_test/.claude/commands/my-command.md\n```\n\n**Step 3: Verify Structure**\n```bash\ntree tests/my_first_test/\n# Should show:\n# tests/my_first_test/\n# └── .claude/\n#     ├── skills/\n#     │   └── my-test-skill/\n#     │       └── SKILL.md\n#     ├── agents/\n#     │   └── my-agent.md\n#     └── commands/\n#         └── my-command.md\n```\n\n**Step 4: Execute Test**\n```bash\npython3 scripts/runner.py execute tests/my_first_test \"Execute my test\" --max-turns 15\n```\n\n**Step 5: Verify Components Loaded**\nCheck telemetry for:\n```json\n{\n  \"available_skills\": [\"my-test-skill\"],      // ← Skills found!\n  \"available_agents\": [\"my-agent\"],           // ← Subagents found!\n  \"available_commands\": [\"my-command\"]        // ← Commands found!\n}\n```\n\n**If components are missing**: Check your directory structure\n\n## Test Creation Principles\n\n### Core Principle: Test Real Conditions\n\n**Tests should mirror actual production usage**, not artificial scenarios.\n\n**Good test** (represents real condition):\n```yaml\n---\nname: file-organizer\ndescription: \"Organize project files by type following conventions\"\n---\n\nYou are organizing a real project with mixed file types.\n\nExecute autonomously:\n1. Scan for all source files (*.js, *.ts, *.py, *.go)\n2. Scan for test files (*.test.*, *.spec.*)\n3. Scan for documentation (*.md, *.txt)\n4. Report current organization state\n\n## ORGANIZER_COMPLETE\n```\n\n**Bad test** (artificial condition):\n```yaml\n---\nname: test-counter\ndescription: \"Test file counting\"\n---\n\nCount the following specific files: file1.txt, file2.txt, file3.txt\n```\n→ Tests contrived scenarios, not real usage\n\n### Test Design Checklist\n\nBefore creating a test, verify:\n\n**Representative of Real Conditions**:\n- [ ] Tests actual workflow, not contrived scenario\n- [ ] Uses realistic data/fixtures (not \"test1\", \"test2\")\n- [ ] Mirrors production environment structure\n- [ ] Exercises real tool capabilities\n\n**Autonomous Execution**:\n- [ ] Skill can complete without user intervention\n- [ ] Clear completion marker present\n- [ ] No decision points that require user input\n- [ ] Self-contained (no external dependencies)\n\n**Appropriate Constraints**:\n- [ ] Specifies WHAT to achieve, not HOW\n- [ ] Provides context/purpose, not step-by-step\n- [ ] Allows Claude's intelligence to work\n- [ ] Includes examples for style-dependent tasks\n\n### Sandbox Structure\n\n```\ntests/<test_name>/\n├── .claude/\n│   ├── skills/              # For skill tests (can have multiple)\n│   │   ├── skill1/\n│   │   │   └── SKILL.md\n│   │   └── skill2/\n│   │       └── SKILL.md\n│   ├── agents/              # For subagent tests (can have multiple)\n│   │   ├── agent1.md\n│   │   └── agent2.md\n│   ├── commands/            # For command tests (can have multiple)\n│   │   ├── command1.md\n│   │   └── command2.md\n│   ├── settings.json        # For configuration tests\n│   └── .mcp.json           # For MCP tests\n└── test_fixtures/           # Realistic test data (optional)\n    ├── src/\n    ├── tests/\n    └── docs/\n```\n\n**Notes**:\n- A test can have 0, 1, or multiple of each component type\n- All components in a test folder are available during execution\n- Use multiple components when testing orchestration, nested workflows, or interactions\n\n### When to Use Multiple Components\n\n**Single Component** (Simple Test):\n- Testing one skill in isolation\n- Testing basic subagent behavior\n- Testing individual commands\n- Quick validation tests\n\n**Multiple Components** (Complex Test):\n- Testing orchestrator calling workers\n- Testing nested workflows (skill → subagent → skill)\n- Testing skill-subagent interactions\n- Testing command chains\n- Testing hub-and-spoke patterns\n\n**Example Use Cases**:\n- **TaskList orchestration**: orchestrator skill + worker skills\n- **Multi-skill workflows**: main skill + helper skills\n- **Subagent composition**: analyzer agent + reviewer agent\n- **Command automation**: deploy command + rollback command\n\n### Compliance Verification\n\nBefore creating components, invoke knowledge skills:\n- Testing/creating skills? → `knowledge-skills` (Agent Skills standard + autonomy patterns)\n- Testing/creating subagents? → `knowledge-subagents` (agent patterns)\n- Testing/creating hooks? → `knowledge-hooks` (event patterns)\n- Testing/creating MCP? → `knowledge-mcp` (MCP standards)\n\n**Always apply autonomous design patterns** from knowledge-skills for reliable non-interactive test execution.\n\n## ⚠️ Common Mistakes to Avoid\n\n### Mistake 1: Wrong Directory\n❌ **DON'T**:\n```bash\n# Creating components in production directory\nmkdir -p .claude/skills/my-test-skill\nmkdir -p .claude/agents/my-agent\n```\n\n✅ **DO**:\n```bash\n# Creating components in test-specific directory\nmkdir -p tests/my_test/.claude/skills/my-test-skill\nmkdir -p tests/my_test/.claude/agents/my-agent\nmkdir -p tests/my_test/.claude/commands/my-command\n```\n\n### Mistake 2: Forgetting to Validate\n❌ **DON'T**: Run test without checking structure\n✅ **DO**: Verify with `tree` or `ls` before execution\n\n### Mistake 3: Missing Completion Marker\n❌ **DON'T**: Create skill without `## SKILL_COMPLETE`\n✅ **DO**: Always include completion marker\n\n### Mistake 4: Wrong Prompt Format\n❌ **DON'T**: \"Use the my-test-skill skill\"\n✅ **DO**: \"Execute the my-test-skill autonomous workflow\"\n\n### Mistake 5: Not Checking Telemetry\n❌ **DON'T**: Assume test ran correctly\n✅ **DO**: Check `available_skills` and `permission_denials`\n\n## Autonomous Test Skill Pattern\n\n### Template for Real-Condition Tests\n\n```yaml\n---\nname: <realistic-test-name>\ndescription: \"Test <capability> in <real condition>. Use when: <trigger>. Not for: <boundaries>.\"\ncontext: fork  # For isolation in most tests\n---\n\n## TEST_START\n\nYou are in a realistic <condition>. Your task is to <outcome>.\n\n**Context**: <real-world scenario description>\n**Resources available**: <tools, skills, agents>\n**Expected output**: <specific format>\n\nExecute autonomously and report findings.\n\n## TEST_COMPLETE\n```\n\n### Degrees of Freedom in Test Design\n\n**High Freedom** (Preferred for most tests):\n- Provide scenario and let Claude decide approach\n- \"Analyze this codebase for security issues\"\n- Claude chooses what to check, how to report\n\n**Medium Freedom** (When specific validation needed):\n- Suggest structure with flexibility\n- \"Check for OWASP Top 10 vulnerabilities; adapt based on what you find\"\n- Claude can add/remove checks based on context\n\n**Low Freedom** (Only for deterministic compliance):\n- Specific checklist when outcome must be consistent\n- \"Verify these specific files exist: .env.example, README.md, LICENSE\"\n- Use sparingly - only when reproducibility matters\n\n### Real Condition Examples\n\n**File System Test** (not \"test1.txt\", \"test2.txt\"):\n```yaml\n---\nname: project-file-scanner\ndescription: \"Scan real project for file organization patterns\"\ncontext: fork\n---\n\n## TEST_START\n\nYou are analyzing a real project's file organization.\n\n**Scan for**:\n- Source files in common locations (src/, lib/, app/)\n- Test files (test/, tests/, *.test.*, *.spec.*)\n- Configuration (*.config.*, *.env.*, settings.*)\n- Documentation (README*, *.md, docs/)\n\n**Report**:\n- Organization pattern used\n- Any misplaced files (sources in wrong locations)\n- Recommendations for improvement\n\n## TEST_COMPLETE\n```\n\n**vs** Artificial Test (AVOID):\n```yaml\n---\nname: file-counter-bad\ndescription: \"Count files\"\n---\n\n## TEST_START\n\nCount these files:\n1. test1.txt\n2. test2.txt\n3. test3.txt\n\n## TEST_COMPLETE\n```\n\n### Prompt Patterns for Autonomous Execution\n\n**Good prompts** (real conditions, autonomous):\n- `\"Audit this real project for security vulnerabilities\"`\n- `\"Organize these actual project files by type\"`\n- `\"Analyze this codebase's architecture patterns\"`\n\n**Bad prompts** (artificial, over-prescriptive):\n- `\"Test if skill can count to 5\"` → Artificial scenario\n- `\"Step 1: Do X. Step 2: Do Y. Step 3: Do Z.\"` → Over-prescriptive\n- `\"Verify that exactly these 3 things exist\"` → Too rigid\n\n### When to Be Prescriptive\n\n**Use Low Freedom (specific steps) when**:\n- Testing critical compliance requirements\n- Validating exact behavior matters\n- Reproducibility is essential\n\n**Example**:\n```yaml\n---\nname: compliance-checker\ndescription: \"Verify required compliance files exist\"\ncontext: fork\n---\n\n## TEST_START\n\nVerify these files exist (compliance requirement):\n- [ ] LICENSE (MIT, Apache, or GPL)\n- [ ] .env.example (environment template)\n- [ ] SECURITY.md (security policy)\n- [ ] CONTRIBUTING.md (contributor guide)\n\nReport missing items with severity.\n\n## TEST_COMPLETE\n```\n\n**Use High/Medium Freedom when**:\n- Exploratory testing (code analysis, architecture review)\n- Creative tasks (documentation generation, design)\n- Complex decision-making (refactoring strategies)\n\n## Before Executing Tests\n\n⚠️ **CRITICAL**: Verify your test structure is correct:\n\n```bash\n# Check your structure\ntree tests/<your_test>/\n\n# Verify skills exist (if any)\nls tests/<your_test>/.claude/skills/*/SKILL.md\n\n# Verify subagents exist (if any)\nls tests/<your_test>/.claude/agents/*.md\n\n# Verify commands exist (if any)\nls tests/<your_test>/.claude/commands/*.md\n```\n\n**If structure is wrong**: See \"⚠️ CRITICAL: Test Skill Structure\" at the top of this document\n\n## Test Execution\n\n**Execute** tests using the runner script. You decide:\n- Order of execution (sequential, parallel, targeted)\n- Which tests to run (all, changed, failed, specific phase)\n- When to stop (on failure, after N tests, completion)\n\n**For batch execution**, use Glob to find tests, then iterate:\n```bash\nGlob: \"tests/*/raw_log.json\"  # Find existing logs\nGlob: \"tests/*/.claude/skills/*/SKILL.md\"  # Find skill tests\n```\n\n### Prompt Strategy for Test Execution\n\n**Single-Skill Tests**\n\n**Prompt template**: `\"[Action verb] the [test-name] autonomous workflow\"`\n\nExamples:\n- `\"Execute the file-system-access autonomous workflow\"`\n- `\"Demonstrate the context-isolation test pattern\"`\n- `\"Perform the autonomous-skill test and report results\"`\n\n**Multi-Skill Orchestration Tests**\n\n**Warning**: Multi-skill chains require interactive mode OR different design.\n\n**Option A**: Single orchestrator skill with forked workers\n- Create orchestrator skill that calls workers via `context: fork`\n- Use imperative prompts: `\"Execute the orchestrator workflow\"`\n\n**Option B**: Separate test executions\n- Run each skill test independently\n- Aggregate results manually\n\n**Do NOT**: Create skills that just describe calling other skills - they won't execute autonomously.\n\n## Result Analysis\n\n**YOU interpret** - don't just report telemetry.\n\n**For quality validation**, invoke `meta-critic` skill to compare: what was requested vs what was delivered vs standards specify.\n\n**Autonomy scoring**:\n- 95% (Excellent): 0-1 denials\n- 85% (Good): 2-3 denials\n- 80% (Acceptable): 4-5 denials\n- <80% (Fail): 6+ denials\n\n**Failure patterns**:\n| Symptom | Likely Cause |\n|---------|-------------|\n| `tool_usage_sequence: []` | Nothing executed |\n| `permission_denials > 5` | Not autonomous |\n| `is_error: true` | Crash/exception |\n| `mcp_servers: []` | MCP not connected |\n| Hook didn't fire | Event mismatch |\n\n**Synthesize findings** into reasoned verdict:\n```\n\"PASS: Skill executed autonomously (0 denials), used expected tools (Bash, Write),\ncompletion marker present. No user intervention required.\"\n```\n\nNOT:\n```\n\"Tool counts: Skill 1, Bash 1. Denials: 0.\"  # Don't just dump data\n```\n\n## Test Validity Assessment\n\nWhen analyzing test results, evaluate:\n\n**1. Representativeness** (Did it test real conditions?)\n- Used realistic data/scenarios: YES/NO\n- Mirrored production usage: YES/NO\n- Tested actual capabilities: YES/NO\n\n**2. Autonomy** (Did it complete independently?)\n- Permission denials: count (target 0-1)\n- Questions asked: count (target 0-1)\n- Completion marker present: YES/NO\n\n**3. Flexibility** (Was Claude's intelligence utilized?)\n- Skill could choose approach: YES/NO\n- Not over-prescriptive: YES/NO\n- Adapted to context: YES/NO\n\n**Tests that fail these checks should be flagged for redesign**.\n\n## Test Plan Management\n\n**You manage** the test plan structure. Use whatever works:\n\n**Option A: JSON plan file** (like `tests/test_plan.json`)\n- Read plan to understand what's pending\n- Edit plan to update status and findings\n- Use structured phases/categories for organization\n\n**Option B: Directory-based discovery**\n- Tests are self-documenting via directory names\n- Use Glob/Grep to discover test status\n- Create separate results files as needed\n\n**Option C: Hybrid**\n- Plan file tracks metadata and status\n- Individual test directories contain raw logs\n- Results aggregated by you into summary files\n\n**You choose** the structure. No prescriptive format.\n\n## Multi-Test Orchestration\n\n**You decide** how to run multiple tests:\n\n**Sequential**: One after another, stop on failure\n**Parallel**: Multiple tests simultaneously (use background processes)\n**Targeted**: Only tests related to changed code\n**Regression**: Re-run previously passing tests\n**Phase-based**: Execute specific test phases from plan\n\nUse standard tools (Bash, Glob, Grep) to discover, filter, and orchestrate.\n\n## Example Patterns\n\n### Example: Complete Test Structure\n\n**Directory Structure** (Single Component):\n```\ntests/file_organizer_test/\n├── .claude/\n│   └── skills/\n│       └── file-organizer/\n│           └── SKILL.md          # ← Your test skill here\n└── test_fixtures/                # ← Real data for testing\n    ├── src/\n    ├── tests/\n    └── docs/\n```\n\n**Directory Structure** (Multiple Components - Complex Test):\n```\ntests/orchestration_test/\n├── .claude/\n│   ├── skills/\n│   │   ├── orchestrator/         # ← Main orchestrator skill\n│   │   │   └── SKILL.md\n│   │   ├── worker-1/            # ← Worker skill 1\n│   │   │   └── SKILL.md\n│   │   └── worker-2/             # ← Worker skill 2\n│   │       └── SKILL.md\n│   ├── agents/\n│   │   ├── analyzer-agent.md     # ← Subagent for analysis\n│   │   └── reviewer-agent.md     # ← Subagent for review\n│   ├── commands/\n│   │   ├── deploy.md             # ← Command for deployment\n│   │   └── rollback.md           # ← Command for rollback\n│   └── settings.json             # ← Configuration\n└── test_fixtures/                # ← Real data for testing\n    ├── src/\n    └── docs/\n```\n\n**Execution** (test with multiple components):\n```bash\npython3 scripts/runner.py execute tests/orchestration_test \"Execute orchestration workflow\" --max-turns 15\n```\n\n**Expected Telemetry**:\n```json\n{\n  \"available_skills\": [\"orchestrator\", \"worker-1\", \"worker-2\"],  // ← All skills loaded!\n  \"available_agents\": [\"analyzer-agent\", \"reviewer-agent\"],     // ← All subagents loaded!\n  \"available_commands\": [\"deploy\", \"rollback\"],                 // ← All commands loaded!\n  \"permission_denials\": 0,\n  \"completion_marker\": \"## ORCHESTRATION_COMPLETE\"\n}\n```\n\n**Validate new skill**:\n```\n1. Create tests/skill_name_test/.claude/skills/test-skill/SKILL.md with autonomous execution pattern\n2. Execute: runner.py execute ... \"Execute the test-skill autonomous workflow\"\n3. Analyze telemetry, form verdict\n4. Update results (Edit JSON or Write findings)\n```\n\n**Regression testing**:\n```\n1. Find all skill tests: Glob \"tests/*/.claude/skills/*\"\n2. Execute each test sequentially\n3. Aggregate results: 10 pass, 1 fail\n4. Report failure, suggest fix\n```\n\n**Phase-based execution**:\n```\n1. Read test_plan.json for pending Phase 2 tests\n2. Filter tests by phase: status NOT_STARTED\n3. Execute in order, update status after each\n4. When phase complete, summarize findings\n```\n\n## Component-Specific Testing Patterns\n\n**Skills**:\n- **What to test**: Actual domain workflows, not artificial scenarios\n- **Real condition**: Create skill that solves real problem in target domain\n- **Autonomy check**: 0-1 permission denials, completion marker present\n- **Example**: Instead of \"test-skill-that-counts\", create \"file-organizer\" that organizes real project\n\n**Subagents**:\n- **What to test**: Real delegation patterns, not toy examples\n- **Real condition**: Task that actually benefits from specialized agent/tools\n- **Verify**: Task tool used, agent-specific tools respected\n- **Example**: Instead of \"test-subagent-for-hello-world\", create \"code-explorer\" using Explore agent\n\n**Commands**:\n- **What to test**: Real automation triggers, not contrived ones\n- **Real condition**: Command that would actually be useful in workflow\n- **Verify**: `disable-model-invocation: true` respected, side effects correct\n- **Example**: Instead of \"test-command-echo\", create \"deploy-staging\" command\n\n**Integration**:\n- **What to test**: Real multi-component workflows\n- **Real condition**: Actual workflow from your project\n- **Verify**: All parts worked together in realistic scenario\n- **Example**: Instead of \"skill-a-calls-skill-b\", test real orchestrator calling real workers\n\n**Hooks**:\n- Check side effects occurred (log files, state changes)\n- Invoke `knowledge-hooks` for event pattern reference\n\n**MCP**:\n- Verify server connected (`mcp_servers` not empty) and tools available\n- Invoke `knowledge-mcp` for MCP standard validation\n\n## Pre-Flight Checklist\n\nBefore executing ANY test, verify:\n\n### Structure Check\n- [ ] Test directory created: `tests/<test_name>/`\n- [ ] .claude directory exists: `tests/<test_name>/.claude/`\n- [ ] Skills directory exists (if testing skills): `tests/<test_name>/.claude/skills/`\n- [ ] Agents directory exists (if testing subagents): `tests/<test_name>/.claude/agents/`\n- [ ] Commands directory exists (if testing commands): `tests/<test_name>/.claude/commands/`\n- [ ] Component files exist (skill, agent, or command files)\n\n### Content Check (for each component)\n- [ ] Skill files have YAML frontmatter (name, description)\n- [ ] Subagent files have proper configuration\n- [ ] Command files have trigger definitions\n- [ ] Components have completion markers (`## SKILL_COMPLETE`, `## AGENT_COMPLETE`, etc.)\n- [ ] Components implement autonomous execution patterns\n\n### Execution Check\n- [ ] Run: `tree tests/<test_name>/` to verify structure\n- [ ] Execute test with runner.py\n- [ ] Check telemetry for `available_skills` (should include your skill)\n- [ ] Check telemetry for `permission_denials` (should be 0-1)\n- [ ] Verify completion marker present\n\n### If Checks Fail\n- **Structure wrong**: Move components to correct location (tests/<name>/.claude/)\n- **Component not in available_***: Check directory structure and file names\n- **Permission denials > 1**: Make components more autonomous\n- **No completion marker**: Add completion markers to all components\n- **Multiple components not loading**: Verify each component is in correct subdirectory\n\n## Test Quality Validation\n\n### Quality Checklist\n\nBefore considering a test complete, verify:\n\n**Real Condition Test**:\n- [ ] Scenario mirrors actual usage\n- [ ] Data/fixtures are realistic\n- [ ] Tests real capability, not artificial constraint\n\n**Autonomous Execution**:\n- [ ] 0-1 permission denials\n- [ ] Completion marker present\n- [ ] No user intervention required\n\n**Appropriate Constraints**:\n- [ ] Specifies WHAT, not HOW\n- [ ] Allows Claude's intelligence to work\n- [ ] Not over-prescriptive\n\n### Test Anti-Patterns\n\n**Anti-Pattern 1: Artificial Test Data**\n```yaml\n# BAD\n---\nname: file-counter\n---\nCount test1.txt, test2.txt, test3.txt\n```\n→ Tests contrived scenario, not real usage\n\n**Fix**: Use real project structure\n```yaml\n# GOOD\n---\nname: project-scanner\n---\nScan project for file organization patterns\n```\n\n**Anti-Pattern 2: Over-Prescriptive Steps**\n```yaml\n# BAD\n---\nname: workflow-test\n---\nStep 1: Read file.txt\nStep 2: Count lines\nStep 3: Report number\n```\n→ No room for Claude's intelligence\n\n**Fix**: Provide outcome, let Claude decide approach\n```yaml\n# GOOD\n---\nname: code-analyzer\n---\nAnalyze codebase for complexity patterns\nReport: Average complexity, outliers, recommendations\n```\n\n**Anti-Pattern 3: Testing Trivial Capabilities**\n```yaml\n# BAD\n---\nname: hello-test\n---\nSay \"hello, world\"\n```\n→ Tests nothing meaningful\n\n**Fix**: Test real capability in realistic context\n```yaml\n# GOOD\n---\nname: service-health-check\n---\nCheck if services are running and report status\n```\n\n## Recording Results\n\n**Structure is your choice**. Examples:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"test_id\": \"skill_001\",\n  \"name\": \"Basic skill execution\",\n  \"status\": \"PASS\",\n  \"verdict\": \"Autonomous execution confirmed\",\n  \"findings\": {\n    \"autonomy\": \"excellent\",\n    \"tool_usage\": \"appropriate\",\n    \"issues\": []\n  },\n  \"log_path\": \"tests/skill_001/raw_log.json\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-01-24T22:00:00Z\"\n}\n```\n\nUse Write/Edit to maintain:\n- Individual test results (in test directory)\n- Aggregated results (summary file)\n- Test plan status (update `test_plan.json`)\n\n## Important\n\n- **You orchestrate**. The runner is just a tool.\n- **You decide** test structure, execution order, result format.\n- **You interpret** telemetry and form reasoned verdicts.\n- **Trust your judgment** on what to test and how.\n- **Be autonomous** - 0-1 questions per test session.\n- **Design test skills for autonomous execution** - Use imperative verbs, clear outputs, completion markers. Recipe-style instructions don't work in non-interactive mode.\n- **Always use specific prompts** - Generic prompts like \"Use the skill\" don't trigger autonomous execution. Use \"Execute\", \"Demonstrate\", \"Perform\" with clear action descriptions.\n- **Tests must represent real conditions** - Mirror actual usage, not artificial scenarios. Use realistic data/fixtures, not \"test1\", \"test2\".\n- **Balance constraints with flexibility** - Specify WHAT to achieve, allow Claude to decide HOW. Use degrees of freedom: High (creative), Medium (guided), Low (compliance).\n","numLines":842,"startLine":1,"totalLines":842}}}
